ONE 12/06/96 AT APPROXIMATELY 05:45, DRIVER OF VEHICLE #1 ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE'S PLANT SITE, HOOKED HIS PRODUCT HOSES ONTO THE WRONG RECEIVING TANK AND BEGAN TO UNLOAD.  THE RECEIVING TANK OVERFLOWED INTO THE TANK DIKE AREA.  THE DIKE AREA WAS NOT LARGE ENOUGH TO HOLD THE OVERFLOW.  PART OF THE PRODUCT (APPROXIMATELY 900 GALLONS) ESCAPED THE CONTAINMENT AREA. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCIES AND THE U.S. COAST GUARD WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED.  PREVENTION-DRIVER WILL NOT BE ALLOWED TO UNLOAD WITHOUT FIRST RECEIVING A SIGNATURE FROM THE CONSIGNEE THAT CERTIFIES THAT THERE IS ENOUGH STORAGE SPACE IN THE RECEIVING TANK TO HOLD THE LOAD AND THAT THE DRIVER IS HOOKED TO THE PROPER RECEIVING TANK.

THE CYLINDER WAS IMMEDIATELY MOVED TO AN AREA OF THE PLANT WHERE IT COULD BE PLACED IN A DRUM CONTAINER OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE WHICH WOULD ABSORB THE CHLORINE GAS AND KEEP IT FROM BEING RELEASED TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  LESS THAN 3 POUNDS OF CHLORINE GAS WAS RELEASED TO AIR.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM NEW HAVEN MANUFACTURING CORP. LOCATED AT 46 BLAKE STREET IN NEW HAVEN, CT TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK ROAD IN BRISTOL, CT, A 55 GALLON CONTAINER WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT AS IT WAS BEING TRANSFERRED FROM ONE VEHICLE TO ANOTHER RELEASING THE CONTENTS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM. ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS ASSOCIATED WITH THE CLEAN UP EFFORTS WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY LISTED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENTS.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, A MANDATORY FORK-LIFT OPERATIONS REFRESHER TRAINING SESSION WAS SCHEDULED FOR ALL FACILITY EMPLOYEES IN ORDER TO REVIEW FORK-LIFT SAFETY AND OPEARTION.

column168: AFTER BEING CLASSIFIED INTO A BOWL TRACK, THIS CAR WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM A SPLIT IN THE TANK CAR TANK.  APPARENTLY FORCES RESULTING FROM COUPLING INTO CARS ALREADY HUMPED IN TO THE TRACK CAUSED THE FAILURE AT THIS WEAKENED POINT.  A STREAM OF ACID WAS ARCHING FROM THE SPLIT TO THE GROUND.  ATSF RESPONDERS CAREFULLY APPLIED TWO OAK WEDGES TO RESTRICT THE MATERIAL TO A FLOW RATE OF LESS THAN ONE GALLON PER HOUR.  IN ADDITION, A CONTAINER WAS THEN POSITIONED TO CATCH THE SMALL FLOW OF PRODUCT.  THE CAR WAS OFF LOADED INTO TANK TRUCKS FOR DELIVERY (COMPLETED AT 1400 ON 12/5). SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION REVEALED A 3/4" WIDE SPLIT ABOUT TWO FEET BELOW THE CAR'S CENTERLINE, AND ABOUT 2" FROM A SIDE LADDER BRACKET.  IT WAS NOT ASSOCIATED WITH ANY OTHER WELD.  INDICATIONS WERE THAT THE RUBBER INNER LINER HAD FAILED AND THEREBY PERMITTED PRODUCT TO REACT WITH THE TANK UNTIL THIS FAILURE OCCURRED.

WE WILL MAKE NO MORE DELIVERIES UNTIL WE OBTAIN A PROPER TANK CHART.  WE CONSIDER THIS MATTER CLOSED WITH NO FURTHER ACTION REQUIRED UNLESS WE HEAR OTHERWISE FROM YOU.

column168: THE UNIT WAS AT THE INTERSECTION OF IH 20 AND 377 S.  THIS IS A "CLOVERLEAF" TYPE INTERCHANGE.  THE REAR TRAILER TIRES LEFT THE ROADWAY AS THE DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO ENTER 377 S ON THE RAMP AND THE UNIT OVERTURNED.  THE TRAILER RUPTURED AND THE CARGO WAS IGNITED BY THE SPARKS FROM THE SKID OF THE UNIT.  BENBROOK FIRE DEPARTMENT AND POLICE RESPONDED AS WELL AS FIRE AND POLICE FROM FT. WORTH.  MISSION IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED OUR SAFETY, ENVIRONMENTAL, AND MAINTENANCE DIRECTOR'S TO THE SCENE. EMTECH WAS CONTRACTED TO DO THE CLEANUP.  THERE WERE NO OTHER VEHICLE'S OR INDIVIDUALS INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT OTHER THAN THE DRIVER AND THE MISSION EQUIPMENT.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO OCCUPATIONAL CLINIC IN ARLINGTON WHERE HE WAS TREATED FOR A MILD BURN TO THE SCALP AND A CONTUSION TO THE KNEE. HE RECEIVED A POST-ACCIDENT ALCOHOL TEST AT THIS FACILITY AND WAS GIVEN A DOT DRUG SCREEN AT THE MISSION FACILITY IN ARLINGTON.  THE DRIVER WAS CITED BY INVESTIGATORS ON THE SCENE FOR "RECKLESS DRIVING."  ALL MISSION RESPONSE PEOPLE ARE ON SITE AS OF THIS PRINTING ASSISTING WITH THE CLEANUP PLANS/EFFORTS.  THERE WAS NO CARGO RELEASED INTO ANY WATERWAYS OR ON ANY SOIL.

CUSTOMER THEN CLOSED THEIR VALVE.  SOME PRODUCT WAS SPLASHED ON REAR OF TANK TRAILER.  CUSTOMER STEAMED THE TRAILER EXTERNALLY TO REMOVE SPLASHED PRODUCT. column168: DRIVER LOADING CRUDE OIL AND ACCIDENTLY OVERFILLED CARGO TANK SPILLING CRUDE ONTO GROUND.  DRIVER TRAINING REVIEWED TO PREVENT.

LOCATION HAS 4 30,000 GALLON TANKS.  WHEN GUAGING TANKS BEFORE DELIVERY, DRIVER FOUND THAT HIS LOAD WOULD NOT FIT IN THE TANK (#1) THAT HE WAS TOLD TO PUMP INTO.  WHEN THE DRIVER CALLED FOR INSTRUCTIONS, HE WAS TOLD TO PUT WHAT WOULD NOT FIT IN TANK #1 INTO TANK #2, #3, OR #4.  WHEN TANK #1 WAS CLOSE TO BEING FULL THE DRIVER SWITCHED VALVES TO MAKE THE PRODUCT GO INTO ANOTHER TANK.  THE DRIVER, HOWEVER, FAILED TO SHUT DOWN THE FLOW OF PRODUCT WHILE MAKING THE SWITCH, AND TANK #1 OVERFILLED.  DRIVER SHUT OFF PRODUCT WHEN TANK OVERFILLED.  THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED ON PROPER ATTENDANCE RULES AND PROCEDURES TO BE FOLLOWED FOR THE SAFE PUMPING AND DELIVERY OF PRODUCTS.

ADM DRIVER LOADED NATURAL GASOLINE IN CORALVILLE, IOWA, AND TRANSPORTED SAME TO THE ADM PLANT IN CEDAR RAPIDS.  THE DOME LID ON TOP OF THE TRAILER WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED AFTER LOADING AND APPROXIMATELY 13 GALLONS OF THE CARGO SPILLED OUT OF TOP HATCH BETWEEN THE LOADING POINT AND THE DESTINATION (AROUND 23 MILES).  THE DRIVER STATES HE DID NOT PHYSICALLY CHECK THE DOME LID SECUREMENT PRIOR TO BEGINNING HIS DISPATCH OR AFTER LOADING DUE TO THE WEATHER AND THE PRESENCE OF SNOW ON TOP OF THE TRAILER. DUE TO THE FACT THAT THE TRAILER WAS LOADED FROM THE BOTTOM AT CORALVILLE, THE DOME LID WENT UNCHECKED DURING THE ENTIRE TRIP.  THE PRODUCT WAS MEASURED (BY COMPUTER) DURING LOADING AND AGAIN, BY ADM PLANT PERSONNEL, DURING UNLOADING.  BASED ON THE TWO READINGS THE LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS PUT AT 13 GALLONS.  THE SPILL OCCURRED OVER THE COURSE OF THE 20+ MILE TRIP.

column168: I WAS AT HOME AT APPROXIMATELY 1830 HRS ON THURSDAY EVENING, DECEMBER 12, 1996, WHEN I WAS NOTIFIED BY TELEPHONE THAT A FLAMMABLE INK SPILL HAD JUST TAKEN PLACE AT CURWOOD, NEW LONDON, WI.  THE SPILL INVOLVED ONE SKID OF 30 SHRINK WRAPPED FIVE GALLON PAILS OF FLAMMABLE PRINTING INK.  THE N&M TRANSFER DRIVER INVOLVED IN THIS SPILL WAS ASSIGNED TO PICK UP THIS TRAILER(#908944) FROM BEMIS INC., OSHKOSH, WI.  NOTIFICATION OF THE SPILL CAME AFTER A DOCK EMPLOYEE FROM CURWOOD, INC. WALKED IN TO THE TRAILER AND SAW OVERTURNED FIVE GALLON PAILS LAYING ON THEIR SIDES LEAKING.  THE SKID WAS AT THE HALF WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  THE BACK HALF OF THE TRAILER WAS OPEN.  THE PAILS WERE LOADED BY BEMIS INC. EMPLOYEES, AND THEY APPARENTLY WERE STACKED THREE HIGH WITH ONLY ONE WRAP OF SHRINK WRAP AROUND THE PALLET.  WHEN THE PAILS FELL OVER THE LIDS CAME UNATTACHED ON APPROXIMATELY 15-20 PAILS.  FIVE DIFFERENT COLOR INKS WERE SPILLED FROM THIS SKID.  MOST OF THE SPILLED INK(80 -90%) REMAINED IN THE TRAILER. SOME INK DID LEAK FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR ONTO THE ASPHALT GROUND SURFACE IN THE RECEIVING DOCK.  WE DISPATCHED TWO OF OUR SUPERVISORS (HAZMAT TECHNICIANS) TO THE SITE WITH FULL HAZARDOUS RESPONSE GEAR AND CLEAN UP MATERIALS. CLEAN UP WAS DELAYED UNTIL A DRIVER COULD BE DISPATCHED TO CURWOOD TO REMOVE THE TRAILER A SHORT DISTANCE FROM THE DOCK.  AFTER THE INK WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR AN N&M DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED FROM OUR NEENAH TERMINAL TO BRING THE TRAILER BACK TO N&M TRANSFER.  SOME FURTHER CLEAN UP WAS DONE AT N&M TRANSFER.  SHORTLY AFTER THAT THE TRAILER WAS SENT TO A LICENSED TANK WASH FACILITY FOR COMPLETE DECONTAMINATION. TWO EMPLOYEES WERE DISPATCHED ON FRIDAY MORNING DECEMBER 13TH TO COMPLETE THE CLEAN UP OF THE GROUND SURFACE AT THE RECEIVING DOCK OF CURWOOD, INC. A TOTAL OF (4) FIFTY FIVE GALLONS OF SATURATED ABSORBENTS WAS TAKEN FROM THE SCENE.
19-0041 X/SCC ARIV MLC 0220/08 WITH SUBSTANCE LEAKING OUT OF TRAILER. CALLED FINDLEY DISPOSAL TO CLEAN UP SPILL.

THIS WAS NOT CONSIDERED A CARGO TANK PACKAGE FAILURE.  AS IDENTIFIED IN THE COVER LETTER, TWO VALVES ARE UTILIZED FOR UNLOADING FUEL INTO TANKS IN THE UNLOADING AREA AT MARSHALL STEAM STATION.  IF ONE IS LEFT OPEN WHILE THE OTHER VALVE IS BEING USED FOR UNLOADING FUEL, THE OPEN VALVE WILL BURP SOME FUEL OUT ONTO THE PAVEMENT.  DUE TO THIS, SIGNS WITH INSTRUCTIONS FOR THE DRIVERS ARE POSTED IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA INSTRUCTING THEM TO ENSURE THAT THE UNUSED VALVE IS CLOSED PRIOR TO USING THE OTHER VALVE FOR UNLOADING FUEL.  DUKE POWER COMPANY WAS NOT THE CARRIER IN THIS INCIDENT, BUT IS SUBMITTING THIS NOTIFICATION AS A COURTESY PER DUKE POWER POLICY. AN INVESTIGATION OF THIS INCIDENT WILL BE PERFORMED BY DUKE POWER COMPANY AND APPROPRIATE ACTIONS TAKEN TO HELP PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCES.

column168: DRIVER STOPPED AT TRUCK STOP AND NOTICED A LEAK FROM THE TRAILER.  HE OPENED THE DOORS AND DISCOVERED TWO METAL DRUMS AND ONE PLASTIC DRUM WERE LEAKING.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND THEN THE SHIPPER SENT A CLEAN UP CREW (OHM) TO THE SIGHT.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED AND LEAKING DRUMS WERE SECURED.  THE CLEAN UP CREW PROPERLY DISPOSED OF THE HAZARDOUS WASTE.

OUR DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF DUMPING OFF FUEL OIL FROM OUR TANKER INTO OUR CUSTOMERS TANK.  OUR DRIVER HOOKED THE PUMP HOSES UP BACKWARDS WHICH CAUSED US TO PUMP PRODUCT OUT OF CUSTOMERS TANK INTO OUR TANKER.  BEFORE THE DRIVER NOTICED WHAT HE HAD DONE IT FILLED OUR COMPARTMENT AND BLEW THE DOME LID OFF AND THE FUEL OIL WENT ALL OVER THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER THEN OPENED THE VAPOR AND SPILLED MORE FUEL OIL ALL OVER HIM AND ALSO MORE ONTO THE GROUND.  CONTAINED THE SPILL WITH SPILL KITS AND FLOOR DRI.

column168: ON DECEMBER 27, 1996, APC UNIT WAS TRAVELING EAST ON SC. #5, NEAR CATAWBA, SC., APPROXIMATELY 2 MILES EAST OF HIGHWAY 21.  AS APC CAME OVER SLIGHT HILL VEHICLE #2(UNKNOWN VEHICLE) WAS TRAVELING WEST IN EASTBOUND LANE. APC DRIVER PULLED TRUCK OFF EDGE OF ROAD TO AVOID CAR.  APC UNIT THEN JUMPED A DRIVEWAY CULVERT, TRAVELED A FEW FEET MORE, OVERTURNED, AND TRACTOR WAS ACROSS HIGHWAY AND TRAILER BLOCKED REMAINING ROAD, SPILLING APPROX. 5,350 GALLONS WHICH TRAVELED DOWN SIDE OF ROAD, THEN DOWN SLIGHT GRADE APPROX. 100 TO 150 YARDS.

column168: TANK CAR FOUND TO BE DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM BOTTOM OUTLET CAP. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  A COPY OF THIS REPORT WILL BE SENT TO THE SHIPPER.

CREW FROM YARD SWITCHER REPORTED STRONG ODOR NEAR THIS TANK CAR.  ATSF RESPONDER ASSESSED CAR AND FOUND SPILLAGE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE CUP OF PRODUCT IN THE MANWAY AREA OF THE CAR.  THE LIQUID WAS WIPED FROM THE AREA.  IN ADDITION, ALL FITTINGS, VALVES AND CLOSURES WERE CHECKED.  THE BOTTOM OPERATED, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS FOUND TO BE FULLY OPEN.  THERE WAS NO APPARENT LEAKAGE OF PRODUCT FROM THE OUTLET AREA AS THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS TIGHTLY APPLIED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR LOADING AT A LOCAL INDUSTRY.  THE SHIPPER WILL RECEIVE A COPY OF THIS REPORT AS A REQUEST TO IMPROVE THE QUALITY OF PROCESSES USED IN LOADING/UNLOADING.

column168: FLAT BED TRUCK WAS LOADED WITH SECURED LOAD.  DRIVER FAILED TO SECURE GP-45 STYLE LIQUID ARGON.  WHEN TRUCK WAS PULLED BY DRIVER FROM LOADING DOCK TO GOSS GAS PARKING LOT, THE UNSECURED LIQUID ARGON TANKS FELL ON THE BED OF THE TRUCK CAUSING THE RUPTURE DISC ON ONE UNIT TO BREAK AND ALLOW AN UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  ACTION WAS TAKEN IMMEDIATELY.  SUPV FOLLOWED PROPER SAFETY PROCEDURES.  FUTURE LOAD CHECKS WILL INCLUDE MANDATORY BINDING PROVISIONS.

THE TRUCK'S ORIGINAL ROUTE OF TRAVEL WAS I-15 BETWEEN SALT LAKE CITY, UTAH AND HENDERSON, NEVADA.  BECAUSE OF AN ACCIDENT THAT CLOSED A SECTION OF I-15 AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT IT WAS DARK AND THE ROAD WAS SLICK AND ICY IN SOME SPOTS. THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED ON THE CURVE AT THE BOTTOM OF A HILL.  THE FLAT BED TRAILER SLID OFF THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND BROKE AWAY FROM THE FRONT TRAILER.  THE TRACTOR AND FRONT TRAILER WERE NOT INVOLVED NOR WERE ANY OTHER VEHICLES.  THE HIGHWAY PATROL WAS NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY. THE DRIVER SET OUT TRIANGLE MARKERS AND DIRECTED TRAFFIC UNTIL THE HIGHWAY PATROL TROOPERS ARRIVED.  THREE THATCHER CO EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM MEMBERS, A TECHNICAL ADVISOR, A MECHANIC, AND A DRIVER WITH ANOTHER TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE DISPATCHED FROM SALT LAKE CITY AND ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 8:10 AM.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ALL CONTAINERS WERE IN TACT AND CLEANUP BEGAN AT 8:40 A.M.  CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED AT APPROXIMATELY NOON OF THE SAME DAY.  THE WRECKER DRIVER TOLD ONE OF THE RESPONSE TEAM MEMBERS THAT HE HAS BEEN CALLED OUT TO HANDLE ACCIDENTS AT THIS PARTICULAR SPOT SEVERAL TIMES IN THE LAST YEAR.  WE WOULD RECOMMEND THAT SIGNS BE POSTED ADVISING CAUTION CURVE AHEAD.  THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING UNDER THE POSTED SPEED LIMIT BUT WAS UNAWARE THAT THERE WAS A CURVE AT THE BOTTOM OF THE HILL.  AS MENTIONED ABOVE THIS WAS NOT THE NORMAL ROUTE OF TRAVEL.  IN THE FUTURE ALL DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED NOT TO PROCEED ON TWO LANE ALTERNATE ROUTES UNTIL CONDITIONS IMPROVE AND THEY BECOME MORE FAMILIAR WITH THE ROUTE.

OUR TRANSPORT WAS UNLOADING FUEL INTO AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK AT FARLEY, IA.  THE CONSIGNEE, PERFECTION OIL, ORDERED THE FUEL TO BE PUT INTO A TANK THAT HAD NO GAUGE ON IT.  OUR DRIVER, NOT KNOWING HOW MUCH THE TANK COULD HOLD, DID AS INSTRUCTED, UNTIL HE DISCOVERED PRODUCT ESCAPING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK.  HE STOPPED PUMPING, CALLED THE PROPER AUTHORITIES AND RECOVERED AS MUCH OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT ON THE GROUND AS HE COULD BACK INTO THE TRANSPORT.  MULLINEX INC OF DUBUQUE, IA WAS CALLED FOR CLEANUP AND DECONTAMINATION PROCEDURES, AND THE CONSIGNEE ASSURED US THAT HE WOULD WORK AT IMPROVING HIS SYSTEM FOR RECORD KEEPING AND FUEL ORDERING.  WE WILL STRESS TO OUR DRIVERS THE IMPORTANCE OF STAYING ALERT IN THIS TYPE OF SITUATION.

column168: ON DECEMBER 30, 1996 AT APPROXIMATELY 1750 HOURS, A RAILROAD TANK CAR, SERIAL NUMBER NATX78376, LOAD OF DICYCLOPENTADIENE, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR WHILE BEING SWITHCED AT KCS BATON ROUGE RAIL YARD. THIS TANK CAR LEAKED ONLY WHEN MOVED, THEREFORE, THE CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED TO PREVENT FURTHER MOVEMENT AND POSSIBLE LEAKAGE. THE SHIPPER, EXXON CHEMICAL, WAS NOTIFIED AND IMMEDITELY DIPATCHED RESPONSE TECHNICIANS TO MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS. THE EXXON CREW DETERMINED THAT THE RELEASE VALVE WAS BEING FORCED DOWN BY A CUT-OFF VALVE HANDLE, WHICH ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE RELEASE VALVE. TANK CAR REPAIRS WERE CONCLUDED AT 2015 HOURS AND THE CARE WAS SUBSEQUENTLY RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.

column168: WOODEN BOX WAS FOUND THAT HAD A STAIN APPARENT FROM SPILLAGE FROM INSIDE THE WOODEN BOX.  UPON OPENING THE BOX FOR FURTHER INSPECTION IT WAS FOUND THAT ONE OF THE FIVE PLASTIC JUGS ON THE INSIDE HAD APPARENTLY LEAKED A LIQUID SLUDGE TYPE PRODUCT FROM ONE OF THE JUGS.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND THE SHIPPER WHO WAS IN CARACASS, VENEZUELA WAS CONTACTED AND ASKED FOR A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  THIS TOOK SEVERAL DAYS.  AFTER THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED IT FOUND THAT IT IDENTIFIED THE PRODUCT AS A ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZ SUBSTANCE, LIQUID, NOS, UN3082.  THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF SUCH AND REQUESTED THAT WE JUST DISPOSE OF THE MATERIAL.  WE ADVISED THAT WE COULD NOT DO THAT AND THAT THE FAA WOULD HAVE TO BE CONTACTED.  AT THAT POINT WE CONTACTED THE FAA IN NASHVILLE, TENN.  ON JANUARY 13, 1997, MR. SAM BUSEY WITH THE FAA CAME DOWN AND DID AN INVESTIGATIVE WRITEUP AND TOOK PICTURES OF THE PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE IS BEING HELD UNTIL HIS RELEASE.  UNDECLARED SHIPMENT.

PLASTIC BOTTLE OF PRODUCT "THE INVISIBLE SHIELD" PLACED INTO A FEDEX PAK (TYVEK TYPE MATERIAL).  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE BOTTLE LEAKED OUT OF THE TOP AS IT WAS NOT SECURED OR PACKAGED PROPERLY.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED BY THE STATION FINDING THE SPILL AND SHE (SHIPPER) INDICATED THAT IT WASN'T HAZ SO WE CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE TO TRY AND GET AN MSDS FOR THE SUBSTANCE SINCE THEY SOLD IT TO THE SHIPPER IN THE FIRST PLACE. THEY GAVE US THE NUMBER OF CHEMTEL WHOM WE CONTACTED AND HAD A COPY OF THE MSDS FAXED WHICH IS ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT.  THE MSDS CLEARLY LISTED THE PRODUCT AS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID WITH 90% ETHYL ALCOHOL AND A FLASH POINT OF 65 DEGREES F.  THE FAA WAS CONTACTED AND HAS BEEN TO THE STATION AND TAKEN PICTURES.  THE ONLY THING LEFT IS THE EMPTY BOTTLE AND PACKAGING WHICH IS BEING DISPOSED OF.  UNDECLARED SHIPMENT.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED TO OUR COMPANY BY EXPEDITORS INTERNATIONAL OF WASHINGTON, INC. ON DECEMBER 3, 1996. THE FREIGHT WAS SCHEDULED TO DELIVER TO ACE HARDWARE IN PERRYSBURG, OHIO. THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED AUTO PARTS, TOOLS,FOOD ADDITIVES, EQUIPMENT AND PAINT RELATED MATERIALS. THE TRACTOR/TRAILER TRANSPORTING THE FREIGHT WAS INVOLVED IN A ACCIDENT ON DECEMBER 3. THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF INCLEMENT WEATHER AND SLICK ROADS. THE VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING EAST BOUND ON I-84, WHEN THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL ON A CURVE DUE TO ICY ROADS, WENT THROUGH A GUARD RAIL AND DOWN A SLIGHT EMBANKMENT. THE VEHICLE CAME TO REST ON ITS SIDE NOT FAR FROM THE BURNT RIVER. THERE WERE NOT ANY INJURIES. ALTHOUGH SOME OF THE FREIGHT WAS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS NOT A MAJOR FACTOR. THE PROBLEM WAS THE FUEL AND OIL, WHICH WAS RELEASED FROM THE TRACTORS FUEL TANKS AND OIL PAN AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT.APPROXIMATELY 100 TO 150 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED FROM THE TRACTORS FUEL TANKS AND APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF OIL WAS RELEASED FROM THE TRACTORS OIL PAN. INITIALLY, THE FUEL AND OIL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND AS WELL AS A SMALL QUANTITY (5 GALLONS) OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. HOWEVER, THE NEXT DAY IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT SOME OF THE FUEL AND OIL HAD MIGRATED INTO THE RIVER. SEA CURTAINS AND BOOMS HAD TO BE PLACED IN THE RIVER TO CONTAIN AND ABSORB THE FUEL AND OIL. THE SOIL WHICH WAS CONTAMINATED BY THE FUEL, OIL AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS REMOVED AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH ENVIRONMENTAL REQUIREMENTS. OTHER CONTAMINANTS SUCH AS PETROLEUM AND CONTAMINATED WATER, WHICH WAS ABSORBED FROM THE RIVER, WILL ALSO BE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF. SALVAGEABLE FREIGHT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR INSPECTION.

column42: ETHYLENE OXIDE OR ETHYLENE OXIDE WITH NITROGEN UP TO A TOTAL PRESSURE OF 1MPA (10 BAR) AT 50 DEGREES C
column168: ON JANUARY 2, 1997, I REPORTED AN ETHYLENE OXIDE RELEASE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  I ALSO SPOKE WITH INDIVIDUALS FROM DHEC IN COLUMBIA, SC. ON DECEMBER 31, 1996, AN ETHYLENE OXIDE RAILCAR BECAME OVER PRESSURIZED AND THE RELIEF VALVE OPENED VENTING ETHYLENE OXIDE AND NITROGEN TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  AN OPERATOR WENT TO THE RAILCAR AND CLOSED OFF  THE NITROGEN VALVE WHICH WAS CONNECTED TO THE RAILCAR. HE ALSO ATTEMPTED TO VENT THE PRESSURE (WHICH WAS APPROXIMATELY 80 PSIA) TO THE SCRUBBER HOWEVER, SINCE THE VENT LINE IS ONLY 1/2", THE RELIEF VALVE CONTINUED TO VENT.  THE PROCESS MANAGER ATTEMPTED TO TRANSFER OXIDE TO AN EMPTY PREWEIGH TANK BUT SINCE THE MANUAL VALVE ON THE CAR WAS NOT OPEN, NO OXIDE WAS TRANSFERRED.  THE RELIEF VALVE RESEATED UPON REACHING 71 PSIA AND THE INCIDENT WAS OVER.  THE INCIDENT OCCURRED BETWEEN 7:15 PM AND 8:15 PM.  USING THE IDEAL GAS LAW AND PARTIAL PRESSURES, WE ESTIMATE THAT 17.2 POUNDS OF ETHYLENE OXIDE WAS RELEASED ALONG WITH THE HIGH PRESSURE NITROGEN. THESE HAND WRITTEN CALCULATIONS ARE ENCLOSED.  OUR INVESTIGATION CONCLUDED THAT THE NITROGEN REGULATOR WHICH REDUCES THE PRESSURE AT THE RAILCARS TO 55 PSIA HAD FAILED.  THIS REGULATOR WAS REPLACED ALONG WITH THE PRESSURES GAUGES.  THE GAUGE WHICH OUR OPERATOR SAID WAS 80 PSIA AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT WAS FOUND TO BE INACCURATE AND IT IS IMPOSSIBLE TO DETERMINE WHAT THE ACTUAL PRESSURE WAS AT THE RAILCAR.  WE KNOW THAT THE RAILCAR RELIEF VALVE IS SET TO RELIEVE AT 75 PSIA.  WE ALSO HAD A THOROUGH INSPECTION OF OUR PRAXAIR NITROGEN SYSTEM AT WHICH TIME THE REGULATORS WERE CALIBRATED AND VARIOUS GAUGES WERE REPLACED.  THE TECHNICIAN CONCLUDED THAT THE MAXIMUM LINE PRESSURE DELIVERED TO THE SYSTEM COULD NOT HAVE EXCEEDED 78 PSIA AND THAT WAS ONLY IF THEIR REGULATOR HAD FAILED ALSO.  WE CONTINUED TO USE THE CAR THROUGH THE NEXT FEW DAYS AND MONITORED THE AREA TO VERIFY THAT THE RELIEF VALVE HAD PROPERLY RESEATED. THE RAILCAR WAS INSPECTED AT THE SHELL FACILITY ON JANUARY 24, 1997. THEY PRESSURE TESTED THE RELIEF VALVE AND VERIFIED THAT THE RELIEF VALVE HAD LIFTED AND THAT IT RESEATED AT 71 PSIA.TO REDUCE THE LIKELIHOOD OF A REOCCURRENCE THE PREVENTATIVE MAINTENANCE SCHEDULE FOR THE RAILCAR REGULATORS HAS BEEN REVIEWED. ALSO, SPECIAL TRAINING IS BEING DEVELOPED FOR THE CHIEF TECHNICIANS ON EMERGENCY TRANSFER OF ETHYLENE OXIDE DURING SUCH AN INCIDENT SO THAT THE AMOUNT OT ETHYLENE OXIDE/NITROGEN WILL BE MINIMIZED.

column168: I RESPONDED TO A LEAKING CORROSIVE ON THE EAST PRIMARY BULK BELT. AFTER CONSULTING DECISION TREE, WHICH LED TO LIQUID CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET, AND DONNING THE PROPER PPE, I MEASURED THE PH OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL, WHICH WAS 1. I THEN USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE TO A PH OF 7, PROCESSED THE DAMAGED PORTION THRU DMP PROCEDURES, AND SENT THE BALANCE TO THE UPS/HERITAGE REPACK PROGRAM TO BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

I RESPONDED TO BAY 139 ON THE EAST PRIMARY TO CLEAN UP A LEAKING PACAKGE. AFTER CHECKING MY DECISION TREE AND DONNING PROPER PPE. I OPENED THE LEAKING PACKAGE. THE OUTSIDE PACKAGE DID NOT HAVE A 5-PLY OR DIAMOND LABELS. UPON READING THE INGREDIENTS OF THE PRODUCT, I REALIZED THAT IT WAS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID. I CALLED THE SHIPPER TO VERIFY. I THEN CONSULTED MY FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET, ADDED SOLUSORB TO THE SOILED MATERIAL, CONTAINED, THEN BROUGHT BACK TO THE DOT CAGE WHERE I PROCESSED THROUGH DMP PROCEDURES AND RTSED THE BALANCE. DIR #6131032

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: DURING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER DISCOVERD THIS CAR LEAKING AROUND THE PACKING OF THE SLIP TUBE GAUGING DEVICE. REEDER TIGHTENED THE PACKING NUT, BUT COULD NOT STOP THE LEAK. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED THROUGH CHEMTREC AND ASKED TO SEND A REPRESENTATIVE TO THE SCENE. JIM GREEN OF TEXAS TANK CAR WORKS ARRIVED ABOUT 230PM. THE GAUGING ROD WAS MOVED A FEW TIMES THEN THE PACKING TIGHTENED AND THEY STOPPED. ANOTHER LEAK WAS DISCOVERED COMING FROM THE UNDER THE VAPOR VALVE. THE NUTS HOLDING THE VALVE WERE TIGHTENED AND AGAIN THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. REEDER ASKED THE SHIPPER TO HAVE THE CAR SENT TO A SHOP FOR INSPECTION AND NECESSARY REPAIRS BEFORE HAVING IT LOADED AGAIN.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: DURING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER DISCOVERED THIS CAR LEAKING FROM THE SAFETY VENT. THE DISK WAS COVERED WITH LIQUID ACID. VAPORS WERE BUBBLING FROM AROUND THE EDGES OF THE DISK. REEDER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER THROUGH CHEMTREC AND ASKED THEM TO SEND A REPRESENTATIVE TO THE SCENE. THE PRESSURE HAD TO BE RELIEVED FROM THE CAR. REEDER ASKED THE SHIPPER TO BRING A DRUM WITH A NEUTRALIZING SOLUTION THAT COULD BE USED TO DEPRESSURE THE CAR. UPON THEIR ARRIVAL, THE PRESSURE WAS REMOVED AND THE LEAK STOPPED. THE NUTS ON THE RETAINER WERE TIGHTENED AND THE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE WITHOUT FURTHER DELAY.

UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIABLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND A QUART METAL CONTAINER OF PAINT.  THE CLOSURE ON THE CAN WAS NOT SECURE CAUSING THE CONTENTS TO LEAK.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE CONTENTS OF THIS SHIPMENT, THEY FOUND ADDITIONAL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THOSE MATERIALS ARE AS FOLLOWS: 6-AEROSOL CANS OF CLEAR STAIN LACQUER, 6-16 OUNCE GLASS BOTTLES OF TURPENTINE, NEITHER OF THESE ITEMS LEAKED.  ALSO INCLUDED IN THIS SHIPMENT ARE PAINT BRUSHES, 2 ROLLS OF WHITE TAPE AND PACKING MATERIAL.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RESEALED, PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM AND IS CURRENTLY ON HOLD IN THE HAZ MAT SORT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR VEHICLE ROLLED OVER ON ITS RIGHT SIDE WHILE MAKING A LEFT TURN.  WHEN THE CARGO TANK LANDED ON ITS RIGHT SIDE THE SECTION OF THE TANK COMING INTO CONTACT WITH THE GRAVEL COVERED ROAD SURFACE WAS PUNCTURED AND RIPPED ALONG A SECTION ABOUT TWELVE INCHES LONG AND ABOUT AN INCH WIDE.  FUEL OIL LEAKED AT THE RATE OF ABOUT ONE HUNDRED GALLONS PER MINUTE FROM THE TANK. CLEANUP AND REMEDIAL OF THE SITE WAS PERFORMED BY INDUSTRIAL MARINE SERVICE OF NORFOLK, VA.  MR. WILLIAM PFEIFLE, VA DEQ ENVIRONMENTAL INVESTIGATOR AT THE ACCIDENT SCENE, ISSUED DEQ FINAL REPORT 3 JANUARY 1997, INDICATING THAT HAZ MAT CLEANUP AND REMEDIAL ACTION WERE SATISFACTORY AND THAT NO PRODUCT HAD MIGRATED INTO VIRGINIA WATERS. CORRECTIVE ACTIONS INCLUDED ADDITIONAL TRAINING PROGRAMS FOR DRIVERS AND DRIVER APPLICANTS CONCERNING NEGOTIATING CURVES WITH LOADED TANKERS.

SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO THE HAZMAT AREA FOR A POSSIBLE SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL RESPONDERS FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WHICH HAD BEEN STRUCK BY A FORKLIFT.  BOX WAS FOUND TO BE FULL OF AEROSOL CANS AND ONE CAN HAD BURST. RESPONDERS PLACED BOX IN A DISPOSAL BAG AND PLACED IN THE DISPOSAL BUILDING AWAITING DISPOSITION BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPARTMENT.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: AT 4:00PM ON 12/17/96 A PORTABLE TANK LOADED WITH 3,220 LBS. OF NITRIC ACID WAS BEING MOVED FROM OUR DRUMMING FACILITY TO A STORAGE AREA AT THE EAST END OF OUR BUILDING.  IN LEAVING THE DRUMMING AREA THERE IS A SLIGHT DOWNHILL GRADE.  THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS COMING OUT OF THE DRUMMING FACILITY AND BEGINNING THE DESCENT DOWN THE GRADE WHEN THE PORTABLE TANK SLID OFF THE FORKS AND SLID TO THE GROUND.  IN DOING SO IT TURNED ON ITS SIDE AND THE 22" MANWAY COVER CAME OFF THE TANK ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 1,840 LBS. OF NITRIC ACID TO SPILL TO THE CONCRETE.  HELP WAS SUMMONED IMMEDIATELY AND A SMALL DAM WAS MADE FROM BICARBONATE OF SODA AROUND THE DRAIN AREA AND AT THE SAME TIME SODA ASH WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE WHAT HAD SPILLED TO THE GROUND.  ALL SODA ASH AND BICARBONATE OF SODA WAS COLLECTED AND PLACED IN OPEN TOP DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.  NO PRODUCT WAS LOST TO THE ENVIRONMENT; NO DAMAGE WAS DONE.  ALL NITRIC ACID WAS CONTAINED ON A CONCRETE PAD, NEUTRALIZED AND IS READY FOR DISPOSAL.  THE TANK WAS RIGHTED AND WEIGHED AND SHOWED A LOSS OF 1,840 LBS.

column168: ON 12/30/96 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT IL IN HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, DISPATH AREA.  THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS IN OUR "C" BUILDING SORT AREA. AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME, SPILL TECHNICIAN, CAROYLN CORDREY RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL, MC. CORDRE DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING AN ODOR.  THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS MARKED AND LABELED AS (RESIN SOLUTION, UN 18660 SHIPMENT HAD FLAMMABLE LABEL AND ORIENTATION ARROWS.  THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX WAS NOT WET.  UPON INSPECTION ON THE INNER CARDBOARD BOXES, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE PRODUCT HAD LEAKED AND SATURATED THE 4 INNER CARDBOARD BOXES.  THE CARDBOARD BOXES WERE MARKED WITH COMPANY LOGO MARKINGS AND THE DIMENTIONS OF THE BOXES, AND INNER GLASS TUBES  FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE INNER MOST PACKAGING REVEALED, EACH CARDBOARD BOX TO CONTAIN (5 GLASS TUBES/RECEPTACLES).  THERE WERE A TOTAL OF (4) GLASS TUBES OF (RESIN SOLUTION) BROKEN, THESE CONTAINED APPROX. (28mm) EACH.  THE TUBES APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN BROKEN AT THE FORWARD ENDS.  THE ONLY PACKAGING MATERIAL WAS LOCATED BETWEEN THE FIBERBOARD BOX AND THE CARDBOARD BOXES.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS BASIC PACKAGE FAILURE.

THERE ARE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR ATTACHMENTS ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THIS IS A REGULATED MATERIAL.

column168: ON 12/26/96 A SPILL WAS REPORTED TO IL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, DISPATCH CENTER.  THE LOCATION OF THE CENTER IS, ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, IHIO 45177.  THE SPILL WAS LOCATED IN C BUILDING, SORT CENTER. PART TIME, SPILL TECHNIAIAN, ALAN HENDERSON RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL MR. HENDERSON FOUND A WET FIBERBOARD BOX. EMITTING A GASOLINE ODOR.  THE BOX WAS WAS LOADED IN A CARGO CONTAINER ON ITS SIDE.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE OUTER BOX IT WAS FOUND TO HAVE AN AIRWAYBILL LABEL ON THE TOP OF THE BOX AND THE WORD "TOP", HAND WRITTEN WITH A BLACK MARKER. THREE SIDES OF THE BOX WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN A BRIGGS AND STRATTON, GASOLINE ENGINE, USED FOR HYDRAULIC LINE HOOK UPS.  THIS SHIPMENT ALSO HAD NEWSPAPER AND CARDBOARD USED AS PACKING MATERIAL, AROUND THE SHIPMENT. THE PLASTIC SCREW TYPE CLOSURE WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE LOOSE.  THE LOOSE CLOSURE WAS THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THE LEAKAGE OF THE GASOLINE. THE GASOLINE TANK HAD A CAPACITY OF (2) GALLONS.  THIS GASOLINE ENGINE WAS A 5 HP/2 CYCLE ENGINE.  THIS GASOLINE TANK APPEARED TO BE FILL, DUE TO THE FIBERBOARD BOX, PACKING MATERIAL AND OTHER FREIGHT BEING SOAKED BY FUEL. THERE WAS NO PACKAGE SPECIFICATION INDENTIFICATION SYMBOLS OR REGISTRATION NUMBER OF PACKING MANUFACTURER.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATION TO INDICATE THIS TO BE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

I MICHAEL A FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, JEFF MCLAUGHLIN RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE WAS ISOLATED.  TECHNICAN MCLAUGHLIN DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPORS CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS.  INSIDE WAS A FIBERBOARD BOX WAS EMITTING AN ODOR. THE INNER RECEPTACLE WAS A PLASTIC RECEPTACLE WITH A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE.  THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THIS CLOSURE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPAINED THIS SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARD ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

ON 122696 AT APPX 6 PM MGR CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER, RECEIVED A CALL FROM UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT TERMINAL MGR, TOM MILNER, STATING THIS CONTAINER HAD LEAKED ONTO THE FLATCAR CARRYING IT. REEDER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER USING THE EMERGENCY CONTACT NUMBER PROVIDED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER.  THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR EMTECH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT.  WHEN THE CONTAINER WAS OPENED, THE LEAKING DRUM WAS FOUND TO BE IN THE NOSE OF THE LOWER STACK.  SINCE THE DRUM WAS NO LONGER LEAKING, IT WAS DECIDED TO PERFORM REMEDIATION THE NEXT MORNING, 12/27.  ON 12/27 ALL DRUMS WERE REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER.  ONE DRUM WAS FOUND WITH A SMALL HOLE ABOUT 6 MM BY 18 MM IN THE CHIME.  IT APPEARS THE CHIME WAS DAMAGED BY A FORKLIFT OR DRUM DOLLY WHEN IT WAS LOADED.  THE UNDAMAGED DRUMS WERE RETURNED TO THE CONTAINER.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  EMTECH HANDLED DISPOSAL OF WASTE MATERIAL.  NOTE:  CHEMTREC WAS NOT NOTIFIED AS THEIR NUMBER WAS NOT ON THE SHIPPING PAPER AS THE EMERGENCY CONTACT.

column168: MGR R M STINE WAS CONTACTED BY JIM SNIDER AT THE ARMOURDALE RIP TRACK ADVISING THAT CAR GATX 22806 WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET. INSPECTION DEVELOPED CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH A TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  REMOVED INTACT SEAL "BN INC IH 230134" FROM STUFFING BOX COVER NOTING PACKING GLAND NUT WAS LOOSE.  WAS ABLE TO TURN THE VALVE OPERATING ROD ONE HALF TURN TO "SNUG" THE VALVE CLOSED THEN TURNED THE PACKING NUT A TOTAL OF THREE TURNS.  APPLIED SEAL "UP K 392562" TO STUFFING BOX COVER. ALSO WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP THREE TURNS WHICH SECURED THIS LEAK.  ALSO NOTED CAR TO BE EQUIPPED WITH A GATX 339-385 STYLE 6 MANWAY COVER PLATE HAVING EIGHT SWING BOLTS.  TWO OF EIGHT WERE HANGING DOWN, THREE OTHERS WERE HAND TIGHT ONLY WITH THE REMAINING THREE WRENCH TIGHT.  REMOVED INTACT SEAL "BN INC IH 229858" FROM MANWAY COVER, OPENED COVER AND FOUND THE MANWAY GASKET TO BE IN GOOD ORDER.  PROPERLY SECURED THE COVER PLATE AND APPLIED SEAL "UP K 392561".  CONTACTED DALE BENDER AT HIGH PLAINS, YORK, NEBRASKA, WHO INDICATED HE WOULD HANDLE THE LOADER.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT APPX 1120 HRS ON 12/23/96, SR SPECIAL AGENT T J BOUDREAUX OVER HEARD AVONDALE YARDMASTER HARDEMAN ON THE RADIO DISCUSSING TANK CAR RCRX 1258 THAT WAS DISCHARGING VAPORS FROM A TOP OUTLET. HARDEMAN PLACED THE TANK CAR IN A SAFE LOCATION.  AGENT BOUDREAUX ARRIVED AT ABOUT 1140 HRS AND MET WITH FRA INSPECTOR JAMES DUNCAN WHO STATED THAT HE WAS IN THE TOWER WHEN HE NOTICED VAPOR LEAKING FROM A TOP OUTLET ON TANK CAR RCRX 1358.  AGENT BOUDREAUX AFTER DONNING PROTECTIVE CLOTHING AND EQUIPMENT MOUNTED THE TANK CAR AND FOUND THE FOLLOWING: 1) THE LIQUID LOADING VALVE HAD BEEN LEFT FULLY OPEN; 2) THE BLIND FLANGE WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED; 3) ONE STUD BOLT WAS MISSING AND FOUND LAYING WEDGED BETWEEN THE TANK AND THE PLATFORM GRATING; 4) TWO BOLTS WERE IN PLACE BUT WITHOUT ANY OUTER NUTS; AND 5) ONE BOLT WAS IN PLACE WITH OUTER NUT LOOSE.  AGENT BOUDREAUX CLOSED THE LIQUID LOADING VALVE AND REPLACED THE 1 STUD BOLT, APPLIED 3 NEW NUTS AND TIGHTENED ALL BOLTS ON THE BLIND FLANGE.  TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  ON 12/27/96 AGENT BOUDREAUX CONTACTED ELSA VILLARREAL OF REAGENT CHEMICAL RESEARCH AND ADVISED HER OF THE EXCEPTIONS.  SHE STATED THAT SHE WOULD HANDLE WITH THE RESPONSIBLE EMPLOYEE(S).

column168: REGIONAL MGR CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L WHITELEY, PORTLAND, OR, WAS NOTIFIED BY ALBINA YARD, PORTLAND, OR, UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT FORCES THAT TRAILER KCSZ 231069, BILLED CONTAINS PAINT, WAS LEAKING. INSPECTION NOTED INTACT SEAL 0656 PROTECTING REAR DOORS.  INTERIOR INSPECTION FOUND 12 - 55 GAL DRUMS OF PAINT.  THESE DRUMS HAD BEEN LOADED INTO TRAILER ON WOODEN PALLETS WITH NO BLOCKING OR BRACING.  THE PALLETS HAD COLLAPSED AND DRUMS DISPLAYED EVIDENCE OF CHIME AND ROLLING HOOP DAMAGE.  ONE DRUM HAD STANDING PRODUCT ON TOP, INDICATING LOOSE BUNGS.  IT WAS IMPOSSIBLE TO DETERMINE HOW MANY DRUMS SUSTAINED DAMAGE THAT RESULTED IN LEAKING CONDITION.  FORWARD PORTION OF TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH ROLLS OF COAL TAR WITH VOIDS ON SIDES AND ENDS.  THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING PRESENT.  PORTION OF THIS LADING HAD SHIFTED.  DOORS WERE CLOSED AND SEAL UPY 753727 WAS APPLIED FOR PROTECTION.  MOTOR FREIGHT FORCES WERE INSTRUCTED TO ADVISE CONSIGNEE OF CONDITION OF SHIPMENT AND THEIR RESPONSIBILITY TO SECURE BEFORE MOVING.

column168: ON SAT THE 7TH OF DEC MYO PETE LOCK NOTIFIED MGR H W RODABOUGH ABOUT TANKCAR TCDX 13263 REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR. INSPECTION REVEALED THE CAR HAD A DEFECTIVE BELLY FLANGE, LEAKING ON ALL SIDES.  ATTEMPTS TO TIGHTEN THE SECUREMENT BOLTS FAILED AS THEY WERE ABOUT TO TWIST OFF.  MGR RODABOUGH STOPPED THE LEAK BY FORCING GORTEX GASKET MATERIAL IN AND AROUND THE FLANGE.  KENNECOTT UTAH COOPER, MR GREG GEARHARDT WAS NOTIFIED.  HE ADVISED THEY WOULD HAVE A CONTRACTOR LOOK AT THE CAR AND SEE IF IT COULD BE FIXED AND MOVED BACK TO THE PLANT AT GARFIELD.  THE CONTRACTOR, TRINITY TANKCAR REPAIR, AGREED THAT THE CAR WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSFERRED.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO TRANSFER THE CAR TO TANK TRUCKS.  TRANSFER TOOK PLACE ON THURSDAY THE 12TH OF DEC.  MGR RODABOUGH MET MR BUCK COWAN, THE LOADING SUPV FOR KENNECOTT WHO ASSISTED WITH THE TRANSFER.  OPERATION COMMENCED AT 0900 HRS AND WAS COMPLETED AT 1230 HRS WITHOUT INCIDENT.

column168: AT 0715 HRS ON 12-01-96, MGR LERCH RESPONDED TO DERAILMENT OF TRAIN NPAS-30, ODESSA, NE MP 196.20, WITH POSSIBLE RELEASE OF HAZ MAT, AS REPORTED BY COUNCIL BLUFFS CORRIDOR MGR.  ON ARRIVAL MGR LERCH WAS MET BY KEARNEY VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPT.  THERE WERE NO IMMEDIATE VISIBLE SIGNS OF RELEASE REGULATED MATERIALS.  IN COMPANY WITH FIRE DEPT PERSONNEL, MGR LERCH CONDUCTED AN INSPECTION OF THE DERAILMENT SITE.  TWO TANK CARS OF REGULATED MATERIALS WERE INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT.  TANK CAR UTLX 640920, CONTAINING RESIDUE SUBSTANCE, LIQUID, N.O.S. CLASS 9.  CAR WAS ON ITS SIDE NOT LEAKING, MINOR DAMAGE.  TANK CAR KCCX 2444, LOAD, CONTAINING SULFURIC ACID, CORROSIVE.  CAR WAS UPSIDE DOWN, RESTING ON LOADING PLATFORM, WITH VALVES, AND QUICK FILL HOLE BURIED IN THE GROUND.  THERE WERE NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF RELEASE.  DAMAGE TO CAR MODERATE. *********** WITH DETRAILMENT CREWS ON SITE, THE CLEARING OF WRECKAGE WAS UNDERWAY.  AT 1150 HRS, TANK CAR UTLX 640920 WAS CLEARED WITH NO RELEASE OF RESIDUE MATERIAL.  AT 1600 HRS, PRIOR TO THE UPRIGHTING OF TANK CAR KCCX 2444, A PIT WAS DUG TO CONTAIN ANY SUDDENT RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THE FIRE DEPT WAS ON SIGHT WITH CHARGED LINES, HWY 30 WAS CLOSED DOWN TO VEHICLE TRAFFIC BY STATE PATROL, A SAFETY BRIEFING WAS CONDUCTED WITH WORK CREWS AND MGR LERCH WAS SUITED IN PPE TO DO ANY PLUGGING AND PATCHING IF NECESSARY. ***************** AT 1645 HRS, TANK CAR KCCX 2444 WAS UPRIGHTED WITH A RELEASE OF LESS THAN 25 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND LATER NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH.  AFTER UPRIGHTING CAR, IT WAS INSPECTED NOTING SOURCE OF RELEASE TO BE FROM THE QUICK FILL HOLE.  3 OF THE 4 SWINGBOLTS SECURING THE QUICK FULL HOLE COVER HAD BEEN KNOCKED FREE BY THE ROLL OVER ACTION OF THE CAR.  ONLY 1 SWINGBOLT WAS IN POSITION SECURING THE QUICK FILL HOLD COVER, PREVENTING THE COMPLETE LOSS OF THE LOAD. ************ 12-2-96: CONTACTED BILL SAWIN, OPERATIONS MGR, TRANSWOOD INC TRUCKING AND GREG GIERHART, TRANSPORTATION MGR, KENNECOTT COPPER. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO OFF-LOAD SULFURIC ACID FROM TANK CAR AND TRUCK TO CONSIGNEE, MIDLAND RESOURCES; ST LOUIS, MO.  THE OFF LOADING AND TRANSPORTAION OF PRODUCT WAS COMPLETED ON 12-9-96 WITHOUT INCIDENT.  THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES, AND NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS WERE IMPACTED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.  NOTIFICATIONS: 0630 HRS, 12-01-96, NEBRASKA DEQ NEIL HEIL, #120196-NH-0630; 0855 HRS, CHEM-TREC, JEFF BOTWINICK, #49953; 1000 HRS, KENNECOTT COPPER, WAYNE STOCKABRAND, DIRECTOR OF TRANSPORTATION; 0905 12-02-96, REGION VII, EPA, WOOD RAMSEY #12026-24-0905.

column168: DRIVER #1: "i WAS HEADING NORTHBOUND HERE ON 19.  AS I ENTERED INTO THE CURVE I OBSERVED A SOUTHBOUND TRUCK ACROSS THE CENTER LINES.  I EASED MY TRUCK OVER AS FAR AS I COULD TO THE RIGHT.  WHEN I COME BACK OVER I FELT THE TRAILER LEAN.  I ATTEMPTED TO KEEP CONTROL OF IT AND APPARENTLY THE TRAILER TILTED AND THE FIFTH WHEEL DISENGAGED FROM THE TRUCK." ******** ACCORDING TO THE STATEMENT OF THE DRIVER AND THE PHYSICAL EVIDENCE FOUND AT THE SCENE THIS ACCIDENT OCCURRED AS VEHICLE #1, A SEMI-TRUCK HAULING GASOLINE, WAS NORTHBOUND ON MO-19.  VEHICLE #1 WAS ROUNDING A CURVE; TRAVELED OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY AND COLLIDED WITH A CULVERT. THE IMPACT CAUSED THE TANKER UNIT OF VEHICLE #1 TO SEPARATE, ROLL, AND COME TO REST ON ITS LEFT SIDE.  VEHICLE #1 TRAVELED BACK ONTO THE ROADWAY, CONTINUED FOR A SHORT DISTANCE, AND CAME TO REST WITH THE FRONT OF THE VEHICLE IN THE RIGHT ROAD DITCH AND THE REAR PARTIALLY IN THE NORTHBOUND LANE.  THE TANKER UNIT WAS DAMAGED ALLOWING FUEL TO LEAK FROM THE FRONT STORAGE COMPARTMENT.  THE FUEL WAS REMOVED BY ACTION TRANSPORT, CUBA, MO. ONE AGENT, ALAN CORTVRIENT, SUPERVISED THE CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP OF THE FUEL THAT HAD LEAKED OUT.  ALSO ON THE SCENE WERE THE CRAWFORD CO SHERIFF'S DEPT, CUBA P.D., CUBA FIRE DEPT, BOURBON FIRE DEPT, AND NORTH CRAWFORD COUNTY AMBULANCE PERSONNEL.  ********* A WITNESS, JIM O HEWKIN, STATED HE OBSERVED A SOUTHBOUND LOG TRUCK PARTIALLY IN THE NORTHBOUND LANE, BUT WAS NOT ABLE TO GIVE A DESCRIPTION OF THE VEHICLE OR GET A LICENSE PLATE NUMBER.

ETTER #1457 HANDLED THE ACCIDENT SEE IL STATE POLICE ACCIDENT #17-96-660. FORT TRANSFER OF MORTON, IL. WAS CONTACTED BY LUCKEY TRUCKING TO DO CLEANUP OF THE SPILL GREAT VEHICLE WAS UPRIGHTED BY SENECA TOWING OF SENECA, IL. column168: WHILE TRANSPORTING A SHIPMENT OF HAZ WASTE DESCRIBED ON THE MANIFEST (SEE ATTACHED MANIFEST NO. 62802) AS "HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID, N.O.S. 9, NA3082, PG II (F006), FREE-LIQUID (WHICH HAD SEPARATED FROM THE SOLID MATERIAL INCIDENTAL TO MOVEMENT DURING HIGHWAY TRANSPORT), BREACHED THE PLASTIC LINER AND TAILGATE AREA AND BEGAN TO SPILL FROM THE DUMP TRAILER AS THE SHIPMENT TRAVELED ALONG I-675, IN BEAVERCREEK, OHIO.  THE DRIVER (EMPLOYED BY DRIVER'S INC., AND CONTRACTED BY ENVIRITE CORP) ATTEMPTED TO CONTROL THE DISCHARGE OF LIQUID BY PLACING ABSORBENT PILLOWS AROUND THE AREA OF THE TAILGATE.  HAZMAT RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM THE BEAVERCREEK FIRE DEPT ARRIVED WITHIN 25 MINS AND PLACED SAND ON THE GROUND SURFACE TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  LIQUID (800 GALS) WAS VACUUMED FROM THE DUMP TRAILER AND TRANSFERRED TO A CARGO TANK.  (SEE ATTACHED MANIFEST - NO. 96122).  THE LIQUID PORTION OF THE WASTE WAS TRANSPORTED TO ENVIRITE CORP FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  ************* RESPONSE PERSONNEL ESTIMATED THE QUANTITY OF LIQUID SPILLED AT THE SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 6 TO 8 GALS, EXCEEDING THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY FOR A F006 WASTE DISCHARGE.  HAZMAT RESPONSE PERSONNEL EXCAVATED 900 POUNDS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL RESULTING FROM THE SPILL.  THE CONTAMINATED SPILL-RESIDUE WAS PLACED IN DRUMS AND SUBSEQUENTLY SHIPPED TO ENVIRITE CORP FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL (SEE ATTACHED MANIFEST NO 96123). THE WASTE REMAINING ON THE DUMP TRAILER WAS TRANSPORTED TO ENVIRITE FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL (SEE ATTACHED MANIFEST 62813).  IN RESPONSE TO THE INCIDENT, DRIVERS EMPLOYED OR CONTRACTED BY ENVIRITE CORP WILL BE GIVEN ADDITIONAL TRAILING COVERING INSPECTION OF VEHICLES AND THEIR CONTENTS, INCLUDING RECOGNITION OF INCONSISTENCIES BETWEEN MATERIALS BEING SHIPPED AND THEIR DESCRIPTION ON SHIPPING PAPERS WHICH COULD POTENTIALLY RESULT IN A SPILL OR RELEASE.

column168: ON WEDNESDAY 12/11/96 @ 2330 A GROUND HANDLING PERSONNEL UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM THE FORWARD LOWER CARGO COMPARTMENT OF AIRCRAFT NO.428EX IN NEW ORLEANS SAT IN A SUBSTANCE WHICH IRRITATED HIS SKIN.  UPON EXAMINATION OF THE COMPARTMENT IT WAS OBSERVED THERE WERE TWO "WET" PACKAGES.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED UNTIL A HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED AND DETERMINED THE SUBSTANCE WAS SHERWIN WILLIAMS INDUSTRIAL MARINE COATING, TILE CLAD HARDNER, PART B AND WHITE PAINT WHICH WAS LEAKING FROM THE TWO BOXES.  THE BOXES WERE CONTAINED AND TURNED OVER TO THE UNITED STATES POSTAL SERVICE.  THE U.S. POSTAL SERVICE ALSO CONTACTED THE SHIPPER EXPLAINING THE PROPER SHIPPING REQUIREMENTS AND PROCEDURE WHEN SHIPPING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE HANDLER WASHED SUBSTANCE FROM HIS EXPOSED AREA AND HAD NO FURTHER ILL EFFECTS.

column168: MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION, D.A. LOW, WAS CONTACTED BY 730 SWITCH ENGINE, THAT THEY NOTED A MTBE ODOR COMING FROM SOUTH 9 TRACKS, CHEYENNE, YARDS.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS LOOSE.  ALSO, TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS WEEPING.  TOOK 2 AND 3/4 TURNS ON BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  TOP OPERATED, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS SECURED PROPERLY.  ALICE MARTIN, COASTAL CHEM, WAS NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS AND HAD TANK CAR B/O AND BILLED TO CAR SHOP.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: TRIAD DRIVER GARY PHILLIPS LOADED AT ROCHE VITAMINS, FREEPORT, TX. APPARENTLY NEITHER HE NOR THE PERSONNEL AT ROCHE CHECKED THE MANWAYS ON THE TRAILER AFTER LOADING OR BEFORE TRANSPORT.  LEAK NOTICED BY CLUTE POLICE OFFICER AND HE STOPPED MR. PHILLIPS.  ROCHE PERSONNEL CLEANED UP SPILLED MATERIAL AND DISPOSED OF THE MATERIALS.  TRIAD HAD REPRIMANDED MR. PHILLIPS AND INSTRUCTED ALL DRIVERS TO PRE-TRIP EQUIPMENT BEFORE MOVING OR TRANSPORTING LOADS.
THERE IS NO VENT ALARM-DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO CHECK TANK.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DRIVER CALLED TO REPORT LEAK IN TRAILER UNIT NO T104.  LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE SUMP AREA OF THE TANK WHERE UNLOADING PLUMBING AND DISCHARGED VALVE ARE LOCATED.  I ASKED GARY GRUBE, THE DRIVER, TO ATTEMPT TO TIGHTEN BOLTS AROUND VALVE, HE DID AND THIS SLOWED THE LEAK SOME WHAT.  WE CALLED OUR INSURANCE COMPANY AND ASKED OUR DISPATCH FOR ANOTHER TRAILER, THE CLOSEST UNIT WAS IN PORTLAND, OREGON., APPROXIMATELY 2 1/2 HOURS AWAY. THE INSURANCE COMPANY HAD FOUND A COMPANY TO HELP WITH CLEAN-UP, REDMOND FIRE DEPARTMENT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS ON SCENE.  GARY HAD PLACED GARBAGE CANS FURNISHED BY JAKE'S TRUCK STOP UNDER THE LEAK AND ALSO BUILT A BURM WITH ABSORBENT TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT.  THE OTHER TRAILER ARRIVED AND WAS ABLE TO TRANSFER THE LOAD.  NORTH WEST FIREFIGHTERS CLEANED UP THE

ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK AT H & R OIL COMPANY WAS OVERFILLED DUE TO DISPATCHING ERROR. APPROXIMATELY 644 GALLONS OF KEROSENE OVERFLOWED THE TANK DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS BEFORE THE DRIVER GOT THE PUMP SHUT DOWN. H&R AND LEWIS PERSONNEL WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED BY THE DRIVER. LEWIS THE NOTIFIED EPA, NRC AGENCIES. ADVANCED TECHNOLOGIES INTERNATIONAL WAS CALLED IN TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT. ABG PETROLEUM CONTRACTORS HAVE SINCE TAKEN OVER THE CLEAN-UP PROCESS AND HAVE INSTALLED MONITORING WELLS. OTHER AGENCIES CONTACTED: DIVISION OF ENVIRONMENTAL AND EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT IN LEXINGTON, ROD RABY - ASSISTANT STATE FIRE MARSHAL, AIR CLAIM SERVICE, INVESTIGATIVE SERVICES DIVISION. THESE TYPES OF SITUATIONS ARE BEING DISCUSSED IN OUR QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETINGS. ALSO, DRIVERS DELIVERING PRODUCT TO ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANKS MUST CHECK WITH FACILITY PERSONNEL BEFORE DROPPING PRODUCT INTO TANK.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: APPROXIMATELY 11:30 AM ON DECEMBER 30, 1996, THE CSI RAIL SWITCH CREW PUSHED THE PRODUCT TANK CART SPOTTED ON TRACK 1102 APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET INTO THE CHLORINE CAR, WTCX 981, MOVING IT APPROXIMATELY 9 FEET FURTHER EAST INTO THE CONCRETE BUMPER AT THE END OF THE SPUR.  THE MOVEMENT OF THE CAR SEVERED THE PIPE NIPPLE WHICH CONNECTED THE CHLORINE TANK CAR UNLOADING HOSE INTO THE UNLOADING HOSE INTO THE UNLOADING PIPING HEADER, CAUSING CHLORINE TO BE RELEASED INTO THE AIR.  UPON SENSING FREE CHLORINE IN THE AIR, THE AUTOMATIC SHUTDOWN SYSTEM CLOSED THE CHLORINE FEED VALVES, MITIGATING THE RELEASE OF CHLORINE TO APPROXIMATELY 60 LBS.  KEMIRON EMPLOYEES WORKING IN THE AREA HEARD THE RAIL CAR HIT THE CONCRETE BUMPER.  THEY CONFIRMED THAT NO ADDITIONAL CHLORINE WAS BEING RELEASED FROM THE RAIL CAR AND NOTIFIED MEL BLAINE, THE PLANT ENGINEER.  AFTER INSPECTING THE ACCIDENT SITE TO ACCESS THE DAMAGE, MEL BLAINE INSTRUCTED ONE OF THE OPERATORS TO GO BACK TO THE OFFICE AND HAVE THE  CSI FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE AGENCIES ON THE NOTIFICATION LIST NOTIFIED.  (IT WAS LATER DISCOVERED THAT DUE TO AN ERROR IN PROTOCOL ONLY THE CSI FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD BEEN CONTACTED).  CSI PERSONNEL ARRIVED AROUND 11:40 AM.  AFTER REVIEWING THE ACCIDENT WITH THE CSI FIRE DEPARTMENT, MEL BLAINE WENT TO SOME NEIGHBORING BUSINESSES TO ADVISE THEM OF THE RELEASE.  NONE OF THE BUSINESSES CONTACTED WERE AWARE OF OF AFFECTED BY THE CHLORINE RELEASE.
